reviews.text: Great station, Rural station with a light 70s refurbishment. Like the old station building. Shame the classic underpass is no more but at least everything else is intact I guess

It's a bit of a walk from the town centre and the station building is a bit on the meh side but it does it's job well enough as a station. A new footbridge linking the platforms has lifts to give step free access and to replace the mess that was a subway. No ticket barriers here. Yet.

reviews.text: Goldaming is located in the Chaterhouse section of Goldaming town and is used by Southwest Trains. built in 1849, as an alternative to the disgraceful Milford, Goldaming is a nice station. There is a parking garage nearby, the station is well maintained, clean, quiet and there is a good amount of seating and benches, the station is also staffed and used by commuters and travellers often. Though it is an exceptional station, it is neglected, the station house is crumbling and in desperate need of repair, there is also cracked concrete in some places as well. I love this station but it is desperate need of work.

The staff at Godalming worked hard in the past to maintain the station. and they won awards In 2004 for Best Miscellaneous Building in the Godalming in Bloom 2004 Competition, in 2005 they won Best Small Station in the South West Trains Station Pride Awards and received a Highly Commended in the National Rail Awards.
In July 2006 the station won the Special Award in the Godalming in Bloom 2006 competition, not only for their display of flowers, but also for the welcoming environment they have created. In August 2006 they won Best Small Station in the 2006 South West Trains Station Pride Awards. 

However the station has since been neglected and needs completely redecorating and the 1849 building needs maintaining. The new waiting room has these seats that no one is able to sit on due to the poor sloping design and there is no waste bin on platform one.
